], "full_text": "Radiology\ncontrast nor exposure to ionizing radiation by MR urogram (MRU).\n• Tumors of the urinary tract show vascularity on doppler and postcontrast\nenhancement on contrast-enhanced CT and MRI studies.\n• Prostatic lesions are best assessed by multiparametric MRI.\n• Distant staging (metastatic work-up) of tumors is done by CT due to its wide\ncoverage area.\n• Genitourinary acute and emergent conditions include trauma, some infections,\nobstructive uropathy and testicular torsion\nMCQs!\n1-How can a calcific urinary stone appear on plain X-ray abdomen (KUB)?\n• A) An ill-defined radio-opaque structure\n• B) A sharply defined radio-lucent structure\n• C) An ill-defined radio-lucent structure\n• D) A sharply defined radio-opaque structure\n2- What is the preferred modality to differentiate renal cyst from renal tumor?\n• A) Kidney, ureter and bladder X-ray (KUB)\n• B) Computed Tomography (CT)\n• C) Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)\n• D) Ultrasonography (US)\n3-What is the advantage of the intra-venous urography (IVU) in genitourinary\nimaging?\n• A) No need for contrast exposure\n• B) No exposure to ionizing radiation\n• C) Urinary tract lesions are visualized as filling defects\n• D) Poorly- functioning kidney can be imaged safely\n4-What is the type of catheter used to perform a retrograde cystography study?\n• A) Supra-pubic catheter\n• B) Transurethral catheter\n• C) Nephrostomy tube\n• D) Angiographic catheter\n5-To examine the urinary bladder by ultrasound, what is the patient asked to do?\n• A) Fast\n• B) Urinate to have an empty bladder\n126"}